<br>
I had more important things to do.<br>
<br>
Vanlaan would be annoyed, I thought to myself, but it would be the last time.  It was time to show him that, despite my youth (as the Teir'dal measure such things) I was an adult, that I had earned my place by his side, and that I could be trusted to follow The Father's path.<br>
<br>
I slunk through the Commonlands until I reached the wall near the gates in western Freeport.  Using the evening shadows to hide my dark-skinned form, I felt carefully for the loose stone that would gain me access to the maze of sewers beneath the city.  Closing it carefully, I listened to make certain none had notices, and then made my stealthy way...<br>
<br>
Home.<br>
<br>
Neriak was the Holy City, but the decrepid houses and stinking sewers were my true home.  The Dismal Rage, where I had served, where I had attempted to lead, and, ultimately, where I had realised that I had failed in my Purpose.  That was why I had convinced Vanlaan that I was ready to help him release his sister from her tomb beneath North Freeport.  That was why I had allowed our presence to be noticed.  That was why I had allowed myself to be captured; because I longed for death.<br>
<br>
I had failed Innoruuk then, and I had failed myself.  I would not fail Him again.<br>
<br>
Although distrustful of me in my current form, my former allies were still willing to trade assistance for coin.  I purchased bandages and large clothes, large enough to hide myself.  A bloodstained robe finished the ensemble; innapropriate for a Champion of the Father to wear, but appropriate for my needs.  Several platinum coins passed hands before the house enchanter was willing to obscure my form; I knew he could not disguise me completely, but through his magic I would be... less noticable.<br>
<br>
Back through the sewers I went, until I was almost back to the doorway to the West Gates.  There, I pulled two small piles of bone chips and tossed them into a mystic symbol.  As I chanted the necromantic spell, they attracted the bones of the dead from nearby and formed into a skeleton.  &quot;Pet, guard here,&quot; I whispered, and winced as, in a sepulchral voice, it hissed &quot;As you command, oh great one&quot; in far too loud a voice.<br>
<br>
The ale I had already drank helped add to my obscuring, as none wished to be near the filthy beggar.  Muttering to myself as I went, I watched alertly through the hood of my cloak for any sign of the one I sought.<br>
<br>
Finally, in the Militia House, I found him.  &quot;Masher,&quot; I said, slurring my voice, &quot;tank the Marsh I found you.  Truth is Good, yeshir, Truth ish Good.&quot;<br>
<br>
His eyes widened.  &quot;A messenger?&quot; he whispered.  &quot;Be quiet.  Have you a message for me?&quot;<br>
<br>
I nodded enthusiastically, and handed him a dirty note.  On it, the wax seal of House Dushire, the leader of the Paladins of Marr.  Naturally, as his daughter, I had several of those house seals hidden in various places around Norrath - you never know when being able to deliver an official message would come in handy.  Naturally, I also knew exactly what the note said - &quot;Follow this servant of the Church to the West Gate.  She will bring you to someone who can enlighten us on the Dismal Rage's activities.&quot;<br>
<br>
Alayle, the paladin - for such he was, despite his pretense; a spy for the Marrs, leaking information of the Militia's activities.  I had known him as a child, before I had turned to Innoruuk.  He had been crafty but loyal then, and I knew he would be used for this purpose.<br>
<br>
&quot;Commander,&quot; he shouted, &quot;this... thing was allowed into the Hall.  I'll be taking it out the gates, where it belongs.&quot;  The commander nodded, not even giving a glance to the soldier.  Grabbing me by the shoulder, he whispered, &quot;Act like I'm forcing you.&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Getsher handsh off me, you bashterd!&quot; I shouted, loud enough to get everyone's attention.  When the paladin tried to cover my mouth, I bit him.  In a moment, his blade was at my throat.  &quot;Too convincing,&quot; he spat.  &quot;We're both on the same side.&quot;<br>
<br>
Under my bandages, I smiled.<br>
<br>
We made our way to the wall where my pet lay in wait.  &quot;Alright, he whispered, &quot;now what?&quot;<br>
<br>
I smiled, and with a gentle touch, sent all my hatred coursing through his body.<br>
<br>
I pulled images from the recesses of my mind, and used them to focus Innoruuk's power into the paladin.  My mother, telling me that I could never be a paladin like my father.  My teachers, refusing to let me train with weaponry, telling me that I would be a healer and nothing more.  My blood-father, preaching about Free Will, yet denying me access to what he termed &quot;forbidden lore&quot;.  Pietro Zarn, scoffing at me and calling me a pitiful worm for trying to follow The Father's will.  Loath as I am to admit it, I even focused on the fury I felt at Grand Inquisitor Val'khan, who, when I was on trial, made no appearance.<br>
<br>
And, of course, formost in my rage was the face of Aravs, the one fully responsible for my becoming Spurned.<br>
<br>
The paladin writhed in the agony of my touch like a man on fire.  With Innoruuk's True Blessing spent for the moment, I shouted, &quot;Pet!  Attack him now!&quot; as I drew out my Bone Bladed Claymore.  Confused by his pain, the paladin screamed in terror as my skeletal minion leapt from the shadows at him, laughing with the madness of death and raking at him with his dirty bony claws.  As the paladin desperately fended off my pet's attack, I used my other gifts to peel away slices of his soul like an onion and used them to lend me strength.  When the spy's agony had gone on enough to entertain me, I finally entered the fray, slashing viciously with my massive sword.  The paladin finally found the strength to shatter the fragile bonds that held my pet together, but could not stand against me.  He fell to the ground, exausted.  &quot;I yield!&quot; he whispered.  &quot;Do what you will, but let me live!&quot;<br>
<br>
A young warrior, seeing the fight, shouted at me.  &quot;Hey!  Stop that!&quot;  Angrily, I pulled back my hood and let the obscuring fade.  Faced with my hate-filled visage, the youngster fled.<br>
<br>
I kneeled before the paladin.  &quot;Do you know me?&quot; I hissed.  He stared at me, trying to focus through his agony.  I could smell the bitter tang of blood as it coursed into the sand below.  When he took too long to answer, I grabbed him by the hair and shouted, &quot;DO YOU RECOGNISE ME?!&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;Aedare... Aedare Dushire...  You're Aedare Dushire!  You're the daughter of the High Paladin!&quot;  The words came out in a confused, horrified rush.<br>
<br>
I smiled.  &quot;And do you know what I am?&quot;<br>
<br>
&quot;You're the one who turned from the Marrs to follow Innoruuk... Aedare the Traitor!  Aedare the Damned!&quot;<br>
<br>
My smile widened.  It was good to be remembered.  &quot;Then tell your precious Marrs that someday... I'm coming for them.&quot;  Tossing him to the ground, I weilded my claymore like an axe, and severed his head.<br>
<br>
Searching through his belongings, I found a few coins, but most importantly, the paladin's Testament of Truth, his most precious posession and the proof I needed to show the head of the militia that I had killed a traitor.  Using my finger as a pen, I wrote &quot;Thus to Marr worshippers&quot; in the Paladin's blood on the wall.  Then, wrapping the head carefully, I made my way to my true home - to Neriak.<br>
<br>
Spurned I might be... but I served the Father.  And soon, all Neriak would know that I was His champion.</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> <p>Innoruuk Guides My Path,
Aedare - "The Blade of L'vanon"
Spurned Shadow Knight of Innoruuk
